07738nam a22008055i 9781800101012DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818001010127 a10.1515/97818001010122doi  a(DE-B1597)674869  a(OCoLC)1237720410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a940.1qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aStudies in Medievalism XXX :bPolitics and Medievalism (Studies) II /ced. by Karl Fugelso.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2021] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b20 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medievalism ;v3000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tI: Essays on Politics and Medievalism (Studies) -- tMedievalism and Gulf-War Politics in Tariq Ali’s A Sultan in Palermo -- tCzech Political Medievalism: Tomáš G. Masaryk and Petr Chelčický -- tRobin Hood Political Memes: Hillary Rodham Clinton, Barack Obama, and the Far Right’s Appropriation of the English Outlaw -- tCry George: Grounding English National Identity in the Age of Brexit -- t“Once More into the Breach!”: Allusions to Agincourt and the Medieval Past in Cross-Channel Political Reporting of Brexit -- tRest in Gold: A Medieval-Like Memorial for German Soldiers at El Alamein -- tProvenance and Reception of Iberian Chivalric Books in English from the Seventeenth to the Twentieth Century: The Case of Anthony Munday’s Palmendos (1589) -- tIn Woden’s Shadow: Anglo-Saxonism, Paganism, and Politics in Modern England -- tThe West Remembers (Its Premodern Self): Nation, Civilization, and the Insular Middle Ages in Game of Thrones -- tII: Other Responses to Medievalism -- tThe Emasculation of Theon Greyjoy -- tGeorge R. R. Martin and the Virgin Martyr: Misogyno-feminism and the (Ab)uses of the Past -- tThe Composite Unity of the Entangled Self in Maria Dahvana Headley’s The Mere Wife -- tFit for Print, Not for Spectacle: Ringling Bros. and the Careful Exploitation of Joan of Arc -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays on the post-modern reception and interpretation of the Middle Ages,This volume continues the theme of its predecessor, addressing how the Middle Ages have been invoked to score political points, particularly with reference to the rise of populism fueled by recent recessions and a pandemic. The nine essays in the first portion of the volume directly address political medievalism in Tariq Ali's 2005 novel on Mideast instability, A Sultan in Palermo; attempts by twentieth-century Czech politicians to anchor their causes in the fifteenth-century Czech hero Petr Chelcický; far-right deployment of Robin Hood memes to slander Hillary Rodham Clinton and Barack Obama; the ways Rory Mullarkey's 2017 play Saint George and the Dragon comments onEnglish national identity relative to Brexit; how national stereotypes have come into play amid cross-channel reporting on Brexit; nationalism in the medievalizing German monument to their fallen at the 1942 Battle of El Alamein;the English-speaking world's reception of Anthony Munday's 1589 book on conduct, Palmendos; nationalism in the self-characterization of two contemporary British Pagan movements; and how various communities in the television series Game of Thrones comment on medieval and/or contemporary nations. Nor are politics entirely absent from the final four articles in the volume, as they examine attempts to promote such particular agendas as toxic masculinity in Game of Thrones; misogyno-feminism there and in the George R.R. Martin book series on which the television program is based, A Song of Ice and Fire; the potential for audience self-realization amid the tension between the individual and the collective in The Mere Wife, Maria Dahvana Headley's 2018 adaptation of Beowulf; and ideal individual and collective behavior as modeled in the Ringling Brothers' 1912-13 spectacles about Joan of Arc. Contributors: Leticia Alvarez-Recio, Susan Aronstein, Matthias D. Berger, Shiloh Carroll, Louise D'Arcens, Laurie Finke, John C. Ford, Alexander L, Kaufman, Stephen Lahey, Scott Manning, Galit Noga-Banai, S.C. Thomson, Ethan Doyle White, Karen A. Winstead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBoris Johnson.  aBrexit.  aJacob Rees-Mogg.1 aAlvarez-Recio, Leticia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAronstein, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Matthias D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Shiloh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD'Arcens, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle White, Ethan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Arcens, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinke, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFugelso, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFugelso, Karl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaufman, Alexander L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahey, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManning, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoga-Banai, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato